1778	  \emph{Existence.} The morphism \(\varphi : \Spec K \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) lands
1779	  in some chart \(U^I\) (\(\Spec K\) has one point), so it is given by a ring map
1780	  \(f : \mathbb{Z}[X^I] \to K\). Among the \(\binom{r}{d}\) minors choose \(J\)
1781	  with \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\) minimal. Because \(P^I_I = 1\) gives \(f(P^I_I) = 1\)
1782	  with \(\nu = 0\), the minimum satisfies \(\nu(f(P^I_J)) \le 0\); in particular
1783	  \(f(P^I_J) \ne 0\), so \(f(X^I_J) \in \mathrm{GL}_d(K)\) is invertible over
1784	  \(K\). Define
1785	  \[
1786	    g : \mathbb{Z}[X^J] \longrightarrow K, \qquad
1787	    g(X^J) = f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\bigr) ;
1788	  \]
1789	  this is the composite of \(\theta_{I,J}\) (\cref{def:gr_transition}) with
1790	  \(f\), so \(g\) defines the same \(K\)-point \(\varphi\), now exhibited as
1791	  landing in \(U^J\).
1792	
1793	  We show every entry \(g(x^J_{p,q})\) lies in \(R\), i.e.\ has \(\nu \ge 0\).
1794	  First, for any size-\(d\) subset \(K' \subseteq \{1,\dots,r\}\) the \(K'\)-minor
1795	  of \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\) is \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\), so
1796	  \[
1797	    g(P^J_{K'}) = \det f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\bigr)
1798	    = \frac{f(P^I_{K'})}{f(P^I_J)},
1799	    \qquad
1800	    \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) = \nu(f(P^I_{K'})) - \nu(f(P^I_J)) \ge 0
1801	  \]
1802	  by minimality of \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\). Now the \(J\)-minor \(X^J_J\) of \(X^J\) is
1803	  the identity, so by cofactor expansion each individual entry
1804	  \(x^J_{p,q}\) (with \(q \notin J\)) equals, up to sign, the minor
1805	  \(P^J_{K'}\) for \(K' = (J \setminus \{j_p\}) \cup \{q\}\) -- the \(d \times d\)
1806	  determinant obtained by replacing the \(p\)-th identity column of \(X^J_J\) by
1807	  the column \(q\). Hence \(\nu(g(x^J_{p,q})) = \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) \ge 0\) for all
1808	  entries, and the entries with \(q \in J\) are \(0\) or \(1\). Therefore
1809	  \(g(\mathbb{Z}[X^J]) \subseteq R\), so \(g\) factors uniquely as
1810	  \(\mathbb{Z}[X^J] \to R \hookrightarrow K\). The corresponding morphism
1811	  \(\Spec R \to U^J \hookrightarrow \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) restricts to \(\varphi\)
1812	  over \(\Spec K\) and lies over \(\Spec \mathbb{Z}\), providing the filler.
1813	
1814	  \emph{Uniqueness.} Any two fillers agree over the generic point \(\Spec K\)
1815	  and, \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) being separated over \(\mathbb{Z}\)
1816	  (\cref{lem:gr_separated}), two morphisms \(\Spec R \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\)
1817	  agreeing on the schematically dense open \(\Spec K\) coincide. This verifies
1818	  the valuative criterion, so \(\pi : \mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \to \Spec \mathbb{Z}\) is
1819	  proper.
1820	\end{proof}
